                  <additions>
                    <list>
                      <item xml:id="e1">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iv(erso) #143r" facs="001 002 145">Fols. ir(ecto), iv(erso), 143r</locus> blank
                      </desc>
                      </item>

                      <item xml:id="e2">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#143v" facs="146">Fol. 143v</locus> pen trial
                      </desc>
                      </item>

                      <item xml:id="e3">
                      <desc>
                      words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#23r #43r" facs="025 045">folss. 23r, 43r, </locus>);
                      and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#94r #98r #99v" facs="096 100 102">94r, 98r, 99v, </locus>);
                      and in the upper margin with a symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#85v" facs="088"> f. 85v, line 6</locus>)
                      </desc>
                      </item>

                      <item xml:id="e4">
                      <desc>
                      The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line.
                      Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size.
                      But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe completes the line of text above or below the end of the line (throughout).
                      This scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#5r #5v #6r #6v" facs="007 008 009">fols. 5r, 5v, 6r, 6v</locus>)
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                    </list>
                  </additions>
